    base:desc "The Digital Twin lifecycle is a model‑driven, continuous loop comprising: 1) Design and device modelling – Building Control Engineers create device families in Autodesk Revit, assigning Instance General UUIDs and IFC‑type classes (e.g., IFCLIGHTFIXTURETYPE). 2) Enrichment and IFC export – the enriched BIM model is exported to the IFC open‑standard format and uploaded to the platform. 3) Semantic extraction – an MDE‑based pipeline parses the IFC, extracts domain‑specific representations (e.g., a CyOnto device catalog) and validates mandatory metadata through an IFC model checker. 4) Transformation & artifact generation – model‑to‑text transformations produce deployable runtime artefacts (REST adapters, Ditto entity models, configuration manifests). 5) One‑click deployment – the framework’s orchestration engine automatically provisions, configures, and launches the DT in the runtime environment with zero manual setup. 6) Operational runtime – real‑time, bidirectional data flow is enabled via Eclipse Hono (MQTT broker) and Eclipse Ditto (digital‑twin store), feeding sensor streams directly into the twin. 7) Runtime re‑configuration – dynamic interface updates and parameter tuning are handled by the platform’s runtime configuration manager, allowing changes without full redeployment. 8) Decommissioning – lifecycle governance follows the Design Science Research artifacts and documentation, ensuring traceability of decisions and artefact lineage. Transition management is automated at each stage, preserving reproducibility and adhering to non‑functional requirements of interoperability, scalability, and maintainability."
